A great feature to cover: **CSS Container Queries**.

They let components adapt based on the size of their *container*, not the whole viewport. This is especially useful for reusable cards, sidebars, grids, and design systems.

### Why it’s worth covering

Before container queries, responsive design mostly depended on viewport width:

```css
@media (min-width: 800px) {
  .card {
    display: flex;
  }
}
```

But that doesn’t work well if the same component appears in both a narrow sidebar and a wide main content area. Container queries solve that.

### Quick example

```html
<div class="card-container">
  <article class="card">
    <img src="image.jpg" alt="">
    <div>
      <h2>Modern CSS</h2>
      <p>This card changes layout based on its container size.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</div>
```

```css
.card-container {
  container-type: inline-size;
}

.card {
  display: grid;
  gap: 1rem;
  padding: 1rem;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

/* Applies when the container is at least 500px wide */
@container (min-width: 500px) {
  .card {
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    align-items: center;
  }
}
```

### Talk angle

You could frame it as:

> “Media queries made pages responsive. Container queries make components responsive.”

It’s a small feature with a big impact, especially for component-based UI development.

