CSS anchor positioning is a great pick — it's genuinely new, solves a real pain point, and demos well in a few lines.

## Why it's worth covering

For years, positioning a tooltip, popover, or dropdown relative to another element meant reaching for JavaScript (or a library like Popper/Floating UI) to measure rects and calculate coordinates. Anchor positioning lets the browser do this natively in CSS — no JS measurement loop, and it even handles flipping when the element would overflow the viewport.

## Quick example

```html
<button class="anchor">Hover me</button>
<div class="tooltip">I'm anchored!</div>
```

```css
.anchor {
  anchor-name: --my-anchor;
}

.tooltip {
  position: absolute;
  position-anchor: --my-anchor;

  /* Place tooltip's top edge below the anchor's bottom edge */
  top: anchor(bottom);
  left: anchor(left);
}
```

The key pieces:
- **`anchor-name`** — labels the element others can anchor to.
- **`position-anchor`** — points the positioned element at that anchor.
- **`anchor()`** — references the anchor's edges (`top`, `bottom`, `left`, `right`, `center`).

## A nice bonus to mention

`position-try-fallbacks` lets the element automatically reposition when it would overflow — the kind of "smart flipping" that used to require JS:

```css
.tooltip {
  position-try-fallbacks: flip-block, flip-inline;
}
```

## Talk tips
- Note the **browser support caveat** — Chromium ships it; Firefox/Safari are catching up, so frame it as "emerging."
- A great framing line: *"This is the browser absorbing a whole category of JavaScript library."*

