# CSS Anchor Positioning

Great pick—it's one of the more genuinely useful recent additions. It lets you position one element relative to another (a popover, tooltip, menu, etc.) entirely in CSS, no JS measurement library needed.

## Quick example

```html
<button class="anchor">Settings</button>

<div class="tooltip" popover>Adjust your preferences</div>
```

```css
.anchor { anchor-name: --settings-btn; }

.tooltip {
  position-anchor: --settings-btn;
  position-area: top span-left;        /* place above, aligned to left edge */
  margin-bottom: 8px;
}
```

That's it—the tooltip tracks the button automatically, including on scroll and resize. You can also use `position-try` to flip it when it would overflow the viewport:

```css
.tooltip {
  position-try: flip-block, flip-inline;
}
```

## Why it's worth the stage time

- Replaces a surprising amount of JS (Floating UI, manual `getBoundingClientRect` logic).
- Pairs naturally with the Popover API—anchor positioning handles *where*, popover handles *behavior*.
- `position-try`/`try-tactics` give you collision avoidance that used to require real work.

