### Why it’s worth covering

Many XSS bugs come from code like this:

```js
element.innerHTML = userInput;
```

Trusted Types lets you enforce a rule: dangerous DOM sinks like `innerHTML` can only receive values created by an approved policy.

### Quick example

Enable it with a Content Security Policy header:

```http
Content-Security-Policy: require-trusted-types-for 'script'; trusted-types app;
```

Then define a policy in JavaScript:

```js
const policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy("app", {
  createHTML(input) {
    return DOMPurify.sanitize(input);
  }
});
```

Now this will be blocked:

```js
document.body.innerHTML = location.hash.slice(1);
```

But this is allowed:

```js
const safeHTML = policy.createHTML(location.hash.slice(1));
document.body.innerHTML = safeHTML;
```

